{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528290"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:40:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:40:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14285"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14285"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.48,0.17,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6980"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108857"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6980"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14285"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91221"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"108"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"10851"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16469"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33194"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33195"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43514"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44415"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45031"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108857"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old Aboriginal man presents to Alice Springs Hospital Emergency Department with a three-week history of productive cough. He has recently commenced high-dose prednisolone for renal biopsy-proven focal segmental glomerulosclerosis alongside trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole prophylaxis. A five-day course of amoxicillin prescribed by his General Practitioner has not improved his symptoms. He is a current smoker with a 20 pack-year history. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 114/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. A chest X-ray is shown below and demonstrates cavitating lesions in the right upper lobe (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pneumocystis jiroveci pneumonia","Pulmonary tuberculosis","Pulmonary melioidosis","Streptococcus pneumonia","Metastatic lung cancer"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of pulmonary tuberculosis, particularly given the clinical context. \u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary tuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E commonly presents with chronic productive cough, constitutional symptoms, and upper lobe cavitating lesions on chest imaging. The patient\u0027s Aboriginal background, smoking history, and recent initiation of high-dose corticosteroids all significantly increase his risk. Immunosuppression can unmask latent tuberculosis infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumocystis jiroveci pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E (PJP) typically presents with dry cough and progressive dyspnoea. While this patient is on immunosuppression, he is already on trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole prophylaxis which would reduce the risk of PJP. The radiological pattern would typically also show bilateral interstitial infiltrates rather than upper lobe cavitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary melioidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present similarly to tuberculosis and should be considered in Northern Australia. However, it typically presents more acutely and is associated with risk factors such as diabetes, excess alcohol consumption, and exposure to contaminated soil or water during the wet season in endemic areas. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E infection typically presents more acutely and would be expected to respond to amoxicillin therapy. The radiological pattern is usually lobar consolidation rather than cavitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetastatic lung cancer\u003C/strong\u003E can present with multiple nodules but typically does not cause cavitation. The three-week duration of symptoms and presence of fever make an infectious cause more likely than malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe failure to respond to standard antibiotics, chronic symptoms, upper lobe changes, and risk factors make tuberculosis the most likely diagnosis. Alongside medical management, appropriate infection control measures including airborne precautions and notification to the local public health unit/centre for disease control are essential. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Upper lobe cavitating pneumonia should raise suspicion for pulmonary tuberculosis.","Recent initiation of high-dose corticosteroids can unmask latent tuberculosis infection.","Failure to respond to standard antibiotics in the context of upper lobe changes should prompt consideration of tuberculosis.","Airborne precautions with N95 mask are required for suspected pulmonary tuberculosis.","Indigenous Australians living in Central Australia have higher rates of tuberculosis compared to non-Indigenous Australians."],"references":["Adigun R, Singh R. Tuberculosis. In: StatPearls [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441916/","Tuberculosis (TB). In: Northern Territory Government | NT Health [Online]. Available from: https://health.nt.gov.au/public-health-notifiable-diseases/tuberculosis-tb","Transmission-Based Precautions. In: CDC Infection Control [Online]. Available from: https://www.cdc.gov/infection-control/hcp/basics/transmission-based-precautions.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91221"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14285"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21803"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21803"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ye0Aq8eDN1SvoJbXHbJOvnWqOz17Kc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ye0Aq8eDN1SvoJbXHbJOvnWqOz17Kc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":392,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91221"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T20:42:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T20:43:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6980"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108857"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading